{
  "wireMagic": "pb3",
  "pens": [ {
  
  } ],
  "wsWinStyles": [ {
  
  } ],
  "wpWinPositions": [ {
  
  } ],
  "events": [ {
    "tStartMs": 720,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Today, I'm chatting with Terence \nTao, who needs no introduction. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4320,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Terence, I want to begin by having you retell \nthe story of how Kepler discovered the laws of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 10400,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "planetary motion because I think this will be a \ngreat jumping off point to talk about AI for math. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 16080,
    "dDurationMs": 1760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I've always had an amateur interest in astronomy. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 18480,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I've loved stories of how the early astronomers \nworked out the nature of the universe. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 24720,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Kepler was building on the work of Copernicus, who \nwas himself building on the work of Aristarchus. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 31040,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Copernicus very famously proposed the \nheliocentric model, that instead of the  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 36160,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "planets and the Sun going around the Earth, the \nSun was at the center of the solar system and the  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 40800,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "other planets were going around the Sun.\nCopernicus proposed that the orbits of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 45120,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the planets were perfect circles.\nHis theory fit the observations  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 50240,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that the Greeks, the Arabs, and the \nIndians had worked out over centuries. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 57600,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Kepler learned about these theories in his \nstudies, and he made this observation that the  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 64160,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "ratios of the size of the orbits that Copernicus \npredicted seemed to have some geometric meaning. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 72160,
    "dDurationMs": 7360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He started proposing that if you take the orbit \nof the Earth and you enclose it in a cube,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 80400,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the outer sphere that encloses the cube almost \nperfectly matched the orbit of Mars, and so forth. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 86320,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There were six planets known at the time and five \ngaps between them, and there were five perfect  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 90640,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Platonic solids: the cube, the tetrahedron, \nicosahedron, octahedron, and dodecahedron. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 95760,
    "dDurationMs": 3120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So he had this theory, which he \nthought was absolutely beautiful,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 98880,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that you could inscribe these Platonic \nsolids between the spheres of the planets. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 104960,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It seemed to fit, and it seemed to him that \nGod's design of the planets was matching this  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 110320,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "mathematical perfection of the Platonic solids.\nHe needed data to confirm this theory. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 116880,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "At the time, there was only one really \nhigh-quality dataset in existence. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 122160,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Tycho Brahe, this very wealthy, \neccentric Danish astronomer,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 128160,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "had managed to convince the Danish government \nto fund this extremely expensive observatory. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 132560,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "In fact, it was an entire island where he had \ntaken decades of observations of all the planets,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 138240,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "like Mars and Jupiter, at least every night for \nwhich the weather was clear, with the naked eye. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 144480,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He was the last of the naked-eye astronomers.\nHe had all this data which Kepler  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 148560,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "could use to confirm his theory.\nKepler started working with Tycho,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 152240,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but Tycho was very jealous of the data.\nHe only gave him little bits of it at a time. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 158960,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Kepler eventually just stole the data.\nHe copied it and had to have a fight with  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 164480,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Brahe's descendants.\nHe did get the data,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 168640,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and then he worked out, to his disappointment, \nthat his beautiful theory didn't quite work. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 173040,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The data was off from his Platonic \nsolid theory by 10% or something. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 177840,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He tried all kinds of fudges, moving the \ncircles around, and it didn't quite work. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 182800,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But he worked on this problem for years and years, \nand eventually, he figured out how to use the data  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 188320,
    "dDurationMs": 7520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to work out the actual orbits of the planets.\nThat was an incredibly clever,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 195840,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "genius amount of data analysis.\nAnd then he worked out that the  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 201680,
    "dDurationMs": 3120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "orbits were actually ellipses, not \ncircles, which was shocking for him. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 206640,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So he worked out the two laws of planetary \nmotion: the ellipses, and also that equal  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 210560,
    "dDurationMs": 6480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "areas sweep out equal times.\nThen ten years later, after  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 217040,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "collecting a lot of data—the furthest planets \nlike Saturn and Jupiter were the hardest for  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 222320,
    "dDurationMs": 8480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "him to work out—he finally worked out this \nthird law, that the time it takes for a  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 230800,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "planet to complete its orbit was proportional \nto some power of the distance to the Sun. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 235680,
    "dDurationMs": 2480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "These are the three famous \nKepler's laws of motion. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 239360,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He had no explanation for them.\nIt was all driven by experiment,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 244080,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and it took Newton a century later to give a \ntheory that explained all three laws at once. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 249520,
    "dDurationMs": 6880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The take I want to try on you is that \nKepler was a high-temperature LLM. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 257520,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Newton comes up with this explanation of why \nthe three laws of planetary motion must be true. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 262800,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Of course, the way that Kepler discovers \nthe laws of planetary motion, or figures  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 266400,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "out the relative orbits of the different \nplanets, is as you say a work of genius. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 269760,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But through his career, he's \njust trying random relationships. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 273680,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "In fact, in the book in which he writes \ndown the third law of planetary motion,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 278000,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it's an aside on The Harmonics of the World, \nwhich is just a book about how all these different  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 284080,
    "dDurationMs": 2640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "planets have these different harmonies.\nAnd the reason there's so much famine  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 286720,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and misery on Earth is because the Earth \nis mi-fa-mi, that's the note of Earth. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 290320,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's all this random astrology, but \nin there is the cube-square law,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 294240,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "which tells you what relationship the period \nhas to a planet's distance from the Sun. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 300800,
    "dDurationMs": 8080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "As you were detailing, if you add that to \nNewton's F=ma and the equation for centripetal  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 308880,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "acceleration, you get the inverse-square law.\nAnd so Newton works that out. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 312880,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But the reason I think this is an interesting \nstory is that I feel LLMs can do the kind of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 318880,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "thing of trying random relationships for \ntwenty years, some of which make no sense,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 322480,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "as long as there's a verifiable data bank like \nBrahe's dataset. \"Ok, I'm going to try out random  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 327600,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "things about musical notes, Platonic objects, \nor different geometries, I have this bias that  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 332800,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "there's some important thing about the geometry \nof these orbits.\" Then one thing works. As long  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 336960,
    "dDurationMs": 7280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "as you can verify it, these empirical regularities \ncan then drive actual deep scientific progress. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 344240,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Traditionally, when we talk about the \nhistory of science, idea generation has  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 348080,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "always been the prestige part of science.\nA scientific problem comes with many steps. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 353520,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You have to identify a problem, and then you have \nto identify a good, fruitful problem to work on. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 359440,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Then you need to collect data, \nfigure out a strategy to analyze  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 363120,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the data, and make a hypothesis.\nAt this point, you need to propose a  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 367280,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "good hypothesis, and then you need to validate.\nThen you need to write things up and explain. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 371360,
    "dDurationMs": 6400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There are a dozen different components.\nThe ones we celebrate are these eureka  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 377760,
    "dDurationMs": 9040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "genius moments of idea generation.\nKepler certainly had to cycle through  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 386800,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "many ideas, several of which didn't work.\nI bet there were many that he didn't even  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 392080,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "publish at all because they just didn't fit.\nThat's an important part of the process,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 397760,
    "dDurationMs": 2960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "trying all kinds of random \nthings and seeing if they worked. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 401440,
    "dDurationMs": 7520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But as you say, it has to be matched by an equal \namount of verification, otherwise it's slop. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 410720,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We celebrate Kepler, but we should also \ncelebrate Brahe for his assiduous data  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 415840,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "collection, which was ten times more \nprecise than any previous observation. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 420960,
    "dDurationMs": 6720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "That extra decimal point of accuracy was \nessential for Kepler to get his results. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 429120,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He was using Euclidean geometry and the \nmost advanced mathematics he could use at  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 435360,
    "dDurationMs": 7600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the time to match his models with the data.\nAll aspects had to be in play: the data,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 442960,
    "dDurationMs": 6480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the theory, and the hypothesis generation.\nI'm not sure nowadays that hypothesis  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 449440,
    "dDurationMs": 7040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "generation is the bottleneck anymore.\nScience has changed in the century since. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 458400,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Classically, the two big paradigms for \nscience were theory and experiment. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 464800,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Then in the 20th century, numerical \nsimulation came along, so you can do  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 469920,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "computer simulations to test theories.\nFinally, in the late 20th century,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 474720,
    "dDurationMs": 3440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "we had big data.\nWe had the era of data analysis. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 479200,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "A lot of new progress is actually driven \nnow by analyzing massive datasets first. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 483760,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You collect large datasets and then draw \npatterns from them to deduce thoughts. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 489040,
    "dDurationMs": 3120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This is a little bit different from how \nscience used to work, where you make a  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 492160,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "few observations or have one out-of-the-blue \nidea, and then collect data to test your idea.  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 497440,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "That's the classic scientific method. Now it's \nalmost reversed. You collect big data first,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 501840,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and then you try to get hypotheses from it.\nKepler was maybe one of the first early  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 507760,
    "dDurationMs": 7440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "data scientists, but even he didn't start \nwith Tycho's dataset and then analyze it. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 515200,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He had some preconceived theories first.\nIt seems like this is less and less the  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 520240,
    "dDurationMs": 8240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "way we make progress, just because the \ndata is so much more massive and useful. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 528480,
    "dDurationMs": 6400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Oh, interesting. I feel like the 20th-century \nscience that you're describing actually very  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 534880,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "well describes what happened with Kepler.\nHe did have these ideas—1595 and '96 is where  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 541120,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "he comes up with the polygons and then the \nPlatonic objects theory—but they were wrong. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 546720,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Then a few years later, he gets Brahe's data, \nand it's only after twenty years of trying random  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 552800,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "things that he gets this empirical regularity.\nIt actually feels a bit closer to Brahe's data  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 558160,
    "dDurationMs": 7200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "being analogous to some massive data bank of \nsimulations, and now that you've got the data,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 565360,
    "dDurationMs": 2640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "you can keep trying random things.\nIf it wasn't for that, Kepler would be  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 568000,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "out there just writing books about harmonics \nand Platonic objects, and there would be  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 573520,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "nothing to actually verify against.\nThe data was extremely important. The  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 579600,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "distinction I was trying to make was that \ntraditionally, you make a hypothesis and  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 584720,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "then you test it against data.\nBut now with machine learning,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 590240,
    "dDurationMs": 6480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "data analysis, and statistics, you can \nstart with data and through statistics  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 596720,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "work out laws that were not present before.\nKepler's third law is a little bit like this,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 603840,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "except that instead of having the thousand data \npoints that Brahe had, Kepler had six data points. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 609040,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "For every planet, he knew the length of \nthe orbit and the distance to the Sun. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 613840,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There were five or six data points, and \nhe did what we would now call regression. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 619200,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He fit a curve to these six data points and \ngot a square-cube law, which was amazing. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 624560,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But he was quite lucky that these six \ndata points gave him the right conclusion. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 630960,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "That's not enough data to be really reliable.\nThere was a later astronomer, Johann Bode,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 637200,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "who took the same data—the distances \nto the planets—and inspired by Kepler,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 643440,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "he had a prediction that the distances to the \nplanets formed a shifted geometric progression. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 648720,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He also fit a curve, except \nthere was one point missing. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 652880,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There was a big gap between Mars and Jupiter.\nHis law predicted that there was a missing planet. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 657760,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It was kind of a crank theory, except \nwhen Uranus was discovered by Herschel,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 662800,
    "dDurationMs": 8240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the distance to Uranus fit exactly this pattern.\nThen Ceres was discovered in the asteroid belt,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 671040,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and it also fit the pattern.\nPeople got really excited that Bode had  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 674560,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "discovered this amazing new law of nature.\nBut then Neptune was discovered,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 680480,
    "dDurationMs": 6400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and it was way off.\nBasically it was just a numerical fluke.  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 686880,
    "dDurationMs": 7440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There were six data points. Maybe one reason \nwhy Kepler didn't highlight his third law as  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 694320,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "much as the first two laws is that instinctively, \neven though he didn't have modern statistics,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 698800,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "he kind of knew that with six data points, he had \nto be somewhat tentative with the conclusions. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 705040,
    "dDurationMs": 7520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "To ask the question about the analogy more \nexplicitly, does this analogy make sense if  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 713680,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "in the future we have smarter and smarter AIs?\nWe'll have millions of them, and they can go out  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 718560,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and hunt for all these empirical irregularities.\nIt sounds like you don't think the bottleneck  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 722400,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "in science is finding more things that \nare the equivalent of the third law of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 728560,
    "dDurationMs": 3280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "planetary motion for each given field, \nso that later on somebody can say, \"Oh,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 731840,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "we need a way to explain this. Let's work out the \nmath. Here's the inverse-square law of gravity.\" "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 738240,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think AI has driven the cost of \nidea generation down to almost zero,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 743200,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "in a very similar way to how the internet drove \nthe cost of communication down to almost zero. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 747920,
    "dDurationMs": 7440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It’s an amazing thing, but it doesn't create \nabundance by itself. Now the bottleneck is  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 755360,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "different. We're now in a situation where \nsuddenly people can generate thousands of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 759520,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "theories for a given scientific problem.\nNow we have to verify them, evaluate them. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 766320,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This is something which we have to change our \nstructures of science to actually sort this  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 771840,
    "dDurationMs": 8160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "out. Traditionally, we build walls. In the past, \nbefore we had AI slop, we had amateur scientists  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 780880,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "have their own theories of the universe, \nmany of which were of very little value. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 787680,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We built these peer review publication \nsystems to filter out and try to isolate  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 793760,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the high signal ideas to test.\nBut now that we can generate these  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 801840,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "possible explanations at massive scale, and \nsome of them are good and a lot are terrible,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 807920,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "human reviewers are already being overwhelmed.\nMany journals are reporting that AI-generated  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 814560,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "submissions are just flooding their submissions.\nIt's great that we can generate all kinds of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 820080,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "things now with AI, but it means that the rest \nof the aspects of science have to catch up:  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 826480,
    "dDurationMs": 7360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "verification, validation, and assessing \nwhat ideas actually move the subject forward  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 833840,
    "dDurationMs": 7920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and which ones are dead ends or red herrings.\nThat's not something we know how to do at scale. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 842880,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "For each individual paper, we can \nhave a debate among scientists  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 846960,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and get to a consensus in a few years.\nBut when we're generating a thousand of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 850560,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "these every day, this doesn't work.\nThere's this incredibly interesting  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 855440,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "question. If you have billions of AI \nscientists, not only how do you gauge  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 859840,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "which ones are real progress, but how do you...\nThis is actually a question that human science  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 863040,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "has had to face and we've solved somehow, \nand I’m actually not sure how we solved this. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 869920,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Let's say in the 1940s, if you're at Bell Labs \nand there are these new technologies coming out. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 877040,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Pulse-code modulation, how do you transfer \nsignals? How do you digitize signals?  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 881200,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "How do you transfer them over analog wires?\nThere are all these papers about the engineering  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 885760,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "constraints and the details, and then there's one \nwhich comes up with the idea of the bit, which has  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 890800,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "implications across many different fields.\nYou need some system which can then look  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 894320,
    "dDurationMs": 2400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "at that and say, \"Okay, we need \nto apply this to probability. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 896720,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We need to apply this to \ncomputer science,\" et cetera. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 900560,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "In the future, the AIs are coming up with \nthe next version of this unifying concept. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 906400,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "How would you identify it among millions of papers \nthat might actually constitute progress, but which  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 910960,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "have much less in terms of general unifying ideas?\nA lot of it's the test of time. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 916320,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Many great ideas didn't actually get a great \nreception at the time they were first proposed. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 921200,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It was only after some other scientists \nrealized that they could take it further  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 925600,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and apply them to their own...\nDeep learning itself was a  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 929360,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "niche area of AI for a long time.\nThe idea of getting answers entirely  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 934080,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "through training on data and not through first \nprinciples reasoning was very controversial,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 939440,
    "dDurationMs": 7520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and it just took a long time before it started \nbearing fruit. You mentioned the bit. There were  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 946960,
    "dDurationMs": 3440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "other proposals for computer architectures \nthan the zero-one that is universal today. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 950400,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think there were trits, three-valued logic.\nIn an alternate universe,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 956640,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "maybe a different paradigm would have shown up.\nThe transformer, for example, is the foundation of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 963760,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "all modern large language models, and it was the \nfirst deep learning architecture that really was  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 969680,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "sophisticated enough to capture language.\nBut it didn't have to be that way. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 973200,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There could've been some other architecture that \nwas the first to do it and once that was adopted,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 980000,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it would become the standard.\nOne reason why it's hard to  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 985600,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "assess whether a given idea is going to be \nfruitful is that it depends on the future. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 989840,
    "dDurationMs": 6880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It depends also on the culture and society, \nwhich ones get adopted, which ones don't. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 998240,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The base ten numeral system in mathematics \nis extremely useful, much better than  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1002880,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the Roman numeral system, for instance.\nBut again, there's nothing special about ten. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1008000,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's a system that is useful for us \nbecause everyone else uses it. We've  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1012240,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "standardized it. We've built all our \ncomputers and our number representation  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1017040,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "systems around it, so we're stuck with it now.\nSome people occasionally push for other systems  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1022800,
    "dDurationMs": 9680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "than decimal, but there's just too much inertia.\nIt's not something where you can look at any given  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1032480,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "scientific achievement purely in isolation and \ngive it an objective grade without being aware  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1039040,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "of the context both in the past and the future.\nSo it may never be something that you can  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1045040,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "just reinforcement learn the same way that \nyou can for much more localized problems. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1053840,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Often in the history of science when a new theory \ncomes up that in retrospect we realize is correct,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1059840,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it seems to make implications that either \nmake no sense because they're wrong, and we  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1065920,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "realize later on why they're wrong, or they're \ncorrect but seem wildly implausible at the time. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1070560,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "As you talked about, Aristarchus had \nheliocentrism in the third century BC. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1078480,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The ancient Athenians were like, \"This can't be \nbecause if the earth is going around the sun,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1083520,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "we should see the relative position of the stars \nchange as we're going around the sun, and the only  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1088000,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "way that wouldn't be the case is if they're so \nfar away that you don't notice any parallax,\"  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1093440,
    "dDurationMs": 2880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "which is actually the correct implication.\nBut there's times when the implication is  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1096320,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "incorrect and we just need to graduate \nto a better level of understanding. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1099360,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Leibniz would chide Newton and disagree with \nNewton's theory of gravity on the basis that  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1105360,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it implied action at a distance, and they \ndidn't know the mechanism, and Newton himself  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1111680,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "was sort of stunned that inertial mass and \ngravitational mass were the same quantity. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1114880,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "All these things later were resolved by \nEinstein. But it was still progress. So  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1119360,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the question for a system of peer review for \nAI would be: even if you can falsify a theory,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1125520,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "how would you notice that it still constitutes \nprogress relative to the thing before? "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1129920,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Often, the ultimately correct theory \ninitially is worse in many ways. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1134960,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Copernicus's theory of the planets was \nless accurate than Ptolemy's theory. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1140640,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Geocentrism had been developed for a \nmillennium by that point, and they had  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1146800,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "made many tweaks and increasingly complicated \nad hoc fixes to make it more and more accurate. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1153920,
    "dDurationMs": 2960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Copernicus's theory was a lot \nsimpler but much less accurate. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1156880,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It was only Kepler that made it \nmore accurate than Ptolemy's theory. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1161200,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Science is always a work in progress.\nWhen you only get part of the solution,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1167040,
    "dDurationMs": 6960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it looks worse than a theory which is incorrect \nbut somehow has been completed to the point  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1174000,
    "dDurationMs": 8720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "where it kind of answers all the questions.\nAs you say, Newton's theory had big mysteries. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1182720,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "They had the equivalence of mass \nand action at a distance, which  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1185760,
    "dDurationMs": 7360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "were only resolved with a very conceptually \ndifferent approach centuries afterwards. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1194880,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Often progress has to be made not by \nadding more theories, but by deleting  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1199040,
    "dDurationMs": 7040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "some assumptions that you have in your mind.\nOne reason why geocentrism held on for so long  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1206080,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "is we had this idea that objects \nnaturally want to stay at rest. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1210720,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This is the Aristotelian notion of physics, \nand so the idea that the Earth was moving…  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1214240,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "How come we weren't all falling over?\nOnce you have Newton's laws of motion—an  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1219200,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "object in motion remains in motion \nand so forth—then it makes sense. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1225280,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Conceptually, it's a very big leap to \nrealize that the Earth is in motion. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1230480,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It doesn't feel like it's in motion.\nThe biggest advances, like Darwin's  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1237040,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "theory of evolution, is the idea \nthat species are not static. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1242880,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This is not obvious because you \ndon't see evolution in your lifetime. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1247840,
    "dDurationMs": 7520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Well, now we actually can, but \nit seems permanent and static. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1257680,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Right now we're going through a cognitive version \nof the Copernican revolution, where we used to  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1263440,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "think that human intelligence is the center of \nthe universe, and now we're seeing that there are  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1267040,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "very different types of intelligence out there \nwith very different strengths and weaknesses. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1274640,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Our assessment of which tasks require \nintelligence, which ones don't,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1278960,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "has to be reordered quite a bit.\nTrying to fit AI into our theories  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1285280,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "of scientific progress and what is hard and \nwhat is easy, we're struggling quite a lot. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1290160,
    "dDurationMs": 2720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We have to ask questions that we've \nnever really had to ask before. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1292880,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Or maybe the philosophers had, but \nnow we all have to deal with it. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1295920,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This brings up a topic I've \nbeen very curious about. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1299600,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You mentioned Darwin's theory of evolution.\nThere's this book, The Clockwork Universe  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1303600,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "by Edward Dolnick, which covers a lot of \nthis era of history we're talking about. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1307360,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He has this interesting observation in there.\nThe Origin of Species was published in 1859. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1312320,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Principia Mathematica was published in 1687.\nSo The Origin of Species comes out two centuries  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1317680,
    "dDurationMs": 2160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "after Principia.\nConceptually,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1319840,
    "dDurationMs": 5105,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it seems like Darwin's theory is simpler.\nThere's a contemporaneous biologist to Darwin,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1324945,
    "dDurationMs": 4495,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Thomas Huxley, who reads The Origin of Species and \nhe says, \"How stupid not to have thought of that.\" "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1329440,
    "dDurationMs": 2640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Nobody ever says that about \nPrincipia, chiding themselves  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1332080,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "for not having beaten Newton to gravity.\nSo there's a question of why did it take longer? "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1337920,
    "dDurationMs": 2480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It seems like a big part of the \nreason is what you were saying. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1340400,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The evidence for natural selection is overwhelming \nin a certain sense, but it's cumulative and  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1343600,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "retrospective, whereas Newton can \njust say, \"Here are my equations. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1347520,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Let me see the moon's orbital \nperiod and its distance,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1351440,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and if it lines up, then we've made progress.\"\nLucretius actually had this idea that species  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1357040,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "adapted to their environment in the first \ncentury BC but nobody really talks about it  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1362880,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "until Darwin because Lucretius couldn't run some \nexperiment and force people to pay attention. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1368960,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I wonder if we'll in retrospect end up seeing \nmuch more progress in domains which have this  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1374560,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "kind of tight data loop where you can \nverify them quite easily, even though  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1380000,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "they're conceptually much more difficult.\nI think one aspect of science is that it's not  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1384400,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "just creating a new theory and validating \nit, but communicating it to others. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1389360,
    "dDurationMs": 6480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Darwin was an amazing science communicator.\nHe wrote in English, in natural language. I'm  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1395840,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "speaking like a—\nNo Lean. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1402560,
    "dDurationMs": 7440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I have to get out of my technical mindset.\nHe spoke in plain English, didn't use equations,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1410000,
    "dDurationMs": 6960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and he synthesized a lot of disparate facts.\nLittle pieces of evolution had been worked out in  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1416960,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the past, but he had this very compelling vision.\nAgain, he was still missing things. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1422960,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He didn't know the mechanism for \nheredity, he didn't have DNA. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1429920,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But his writing style was persuasive, and \nthat helped a lot. Newton wrote in Latin.  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1437600,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He had invented entire new areas of \nmathematics just to explain what he was doing. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1442720,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He was also from an era where scientists \nwere much more secretive and competitive. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1447600,
    "dDurationMs": 3280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Academia is still competitive, but it \nwas even worse back in Newton's day. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1451920,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He held back some of his best insights because \nhe didn't want his rivals to get any advantage. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1457600,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He was also a somewhat unpleasant \nperson from what I gather. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1463040,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It was only a couple of decades after Newton \nwhen other scientists explained his work in  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1468480,
    "dDurationMs": 10640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "much simpler terms that they became widespread.\nThe art of exposition and making a case and  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1479120,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "creating a narrative is also a \nvery important part of science. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1485280,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "If you have the data, it helps, but people need \nto be convinced, otherwise they will not push  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1490320,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it further or take the initial investment \nto learn your theory and really explore it. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1498000,
    "dDurationMs": 2640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "That's another thing which is really \nhard to reinforcement learn on. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1501440,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "How can you score how persuasive you are?\nWell, there are entire marketing  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1505600,
    "dDurationMs": 3120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "departments trying to do this.\nMaybe it's good that AI is not  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1508720,
    "dDurationMs": 7360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "yet optimized to be persuasive.\nThere's a social aspect to science. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1519120,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Even though we pride ourselves on having an \nobjective side to it, where there's data and  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1523520,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "experiment and validation, we still have \nto tell stories and convince our fellow  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1528480,
    "dDurationMs": 13040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "scientists. That's a soft, squishy thing. It's \na combination of data and painting a narrative,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1541520,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and it's a narrative of gaps.\nEven with Darwin, as I said, there  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1546560,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "were pieces of his theory he could not explain.\nBut he could still make a case that in the future,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1551200,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "people would find transitional \nforms, that they would find the  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1554960,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "mechanism of inheritance, and they did.\nI don't know how you can quantify that  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1561280,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "in such a precise way that you can \nstart doing reinforcement learning. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1566320,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Maybe that will be forever \nthe human side of science. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1570880,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "One takeaway I had from reading and watching your \nstuff on the cosmic distance ladder… By the way,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1576880,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I highly recommend people watch your series \nwith 3Blue1Brown on the cosmic distance ladder. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1582560,
    "dDurationMs": 7680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "One takeaway was that the deductive \noverhang in many fields could be  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1590240,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "so much bigger than people realize.\nIf you just had the right insight about  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1593600,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "how to study a problem, you might be surprised \nat how much more you could learn about the world. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1598800,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I wonder if you think that's a product \nof astronomy at the particular times  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1603120,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "in history that you're studying.\nOr is it just that based on the data  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1606960,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that is incident on the Earth right now, we could \nactually divine a lot more than we happen to know? "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1612560,
    "dDurationMs": 6720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Astronomy was one of the first sciences to \nreally embrace data analysis and squeezing  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1619280,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "every last possible drop of information out \nof the information they had because data was  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1624400,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the bottleneck. It still is the bottleneck. \nIt's really hard to collect astronomical data. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1630160,
    "dDurationMs": 10000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Astronomers are world-class in \nextracting all kinds of conclusions  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1640160,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "from little traces of data, almost like Sherlock.\nI hear that for a lot of quant hedge funds, their  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1646400,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "preferred hire is an astronomy PhD, actually.\nThey are also very interested for other reasons  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1651280,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "in extracting signals from \nvarious random bits of data. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1655120,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Okay, speaking of clever ideas, \none of my listeners, Shawn,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1659040,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "solved the puzzle that Jane Street made for my \naudience and posted a great walkthrough on X. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1664160,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "For context, Jane Street trained a ResNet, \nshuffled all 96 layers, and then challenged  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1670000,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "people to put them back in the right order using \nonly the model's outputs and training data. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1674640,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You can't brute force this – there's more \npossible orderings than atoms in the universe. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1678880,
    "dDurationMs": 2560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So Shawn broke the problem \ninto two different parts. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1681440,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "First, pair the layers into 48 different blocks.\nAnd second, put those blocks in the right order. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1686880,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "For pairing, Shawn realized that in \na well-trained ResNet, the product of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1691360,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "two weight matrices in a residual block should \nhave a distinctive negative diagonal pattern. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1696640,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This arises as a way for the model to keep the \nresidual stream from growing out of control. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1700400,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "From this insight, he was able \nto recover the right pairings. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1703440,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "For ordering, Shawn noticed that the model \nseemed to improve if he sorted the blocks by  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1708080,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the size of their residual contributions.\nStarting with that rough approximation,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1711680,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "he combined a clever ranking heuristic with \nlocal swaps to recover the exact right order. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1716640,
    "dDurationMs": 2480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "His full walkthrough is linked in the description. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1719120,
    "dDurationMs": 1840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Don't worry if you didn't get \nto this puzzle in time, though. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1720960,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There's still one up about backdoored LLMs that \neven Jane Street doesn't know how to solve. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1724960,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You can find it at janestreet.com/dwarkesh.\nAlright, back to Terence! "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1731200,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We do under-explore how to extract \nextra information from various signals. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1740640,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Just to pick one random study, I remember reading \nonce that people were trying to measure how often  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1746800,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "scientists actually read the papers \nthat they cite. How do you measure  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1752480,
    "dDurationMs": 7440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "this? You could try to survey different \nscientists, but they had a clever trick. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1761280,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Many citations have little typos, like a \nnumber is wrong or punctuation is almost wrong. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1768000,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "They measured how often a typo got copied \nfrom one reference to the next, and they  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1773680,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "could infer whether an author was just copying and \npasting a reference without actually checking it. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1780880,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "From that, they were able to infer some measure \nof how much attention people were paying. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1786960,
    "dDurationMs": 7200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So there are some clever tricks to extract…\nThese questions you posed earlier of how  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1794160,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "we can assess whether a scientific development \nis fruitful, interesting, or represents real  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1800800,
    "dDurationMs": 10400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "progress… Maybe there are really useful metrics \nor footprints of this phenomenon in data. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1812240,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We can examine citations and how often \nsomething is mentioned in a conference. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1817680,
    "dDurationMs": 7760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Maybe there's a lot of sociology of science \nresearch to be done that could actually  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1825440,
    "dDurationMs": 2400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "detect these things.\nMaybe we should get  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1827840,
    "dDurationMs": 9120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "some astronomers on the case, actually.\nThat brings us nicely to the progress that, from  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1836960,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the outside, it seems like AI for math is making.\nYou had a post recently where you pointed out  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1841360,
    "dDurationMs": 3440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that over the last few months, \nAI programs have solved fifty  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1844800,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "out of the eleven hundred odd Erdős problems.\nI don’t know if it’s still correct, but as of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1850800,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "a month ago you said that there had been a pause \nbecause the low-hanging fruit had been picked. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1855360,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "First of all, I'm curious if that is still the \ncase, that we have picked the low-hanging fruit  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1859600,
    "dDurationMs": 7760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and now we're at this plateau currently.\nIt does seem so. Fifty-odd problems have  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1867360,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "been solved with AI assistance, which is \ngreat, but there's like six hundred to go. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1872160,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "People are still chipping away \nat one or two of these right now. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1877600,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We're seeing a lot fewer pure AI solutions \nnow where the AI just one-shots the problem. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1884640,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There was a month where that happened and \nthat has stopped, not for lack of trying. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1888400,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I know of three separate attempts to get \nfrontier model AIs to just attack every  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1893920,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "single one of the problems simultaneously.\nThey pick out some minor observations,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1898800,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "or maybe they find that some problem was already \nsolved in the literature, but there hasn't been  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1903040,
    "dDurationMs": 7520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "any further purely AI-powered solution yet.\nPeople are using AI a lot currently. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1910560,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Someone might use AI to generate a possible \nproof strategy, and then another person will  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1915600,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "use a separate AI tool to critique it, rewrite \nit, generate some numerical data for it,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1921600,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "or do a literature survey.\nSome problems have been solved  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1926240,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "by an ongoing conversation between \nlots of humans and lots of AI tools. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1931520,
    "dDurationMs": 8400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But it does seem like it was this one-off thing.\nMaybe one analogy for these problems is  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1942880,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that you're in some sort of mountain \nrange with all kinds of cliffs and walls. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1947120,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Maybe there's a little wall which is three \nfeet high, and one that's six feet high,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1953680,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and then there's fifteen feet high, and \nthen there are some mile-high cliffs. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1959120,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You're trying to climb as many of these \ncliffs as possible, but it's in the dark. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1963040,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We don't know which ones are \ntall, which ones are short. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1966880,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So we try to light some candles \nand make some maps, and slowly we  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1970720,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "figure out some of them are climbable.\nSome of them we can identify a partial  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1976960,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "track in the wall that you can reach first.\nThese AI tools, they're like jumping  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1982240,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "machines that can jump two meters \nin the air, higher than any human. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1986960,
    "dDurationMs": 2480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Sometimes they jump in the wrong \ndirection, and sometimes they crash,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1989440,
    "dDurationMs": 9360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but sometimes they can reach the tops of the \nlowest walls that we couldn't reach before. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 1998800,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We've just set them loose in this \nmountain range, hopping around. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2003120,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There was this exciting period where they could \nactually find all the low ones and reach them. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2012880,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Maybe the next time there's a big \nadvance in the models, they will  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2016960,
    "dDurationMs": 8800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "try it again, and a few more will be breached.\nBut it's a different style of doing mathematics. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2028320,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Normally we would hill climb, make little \nmarkers, and try to identify partial things. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2036560,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "These tools either succeed or they fail.\nThey've been really bad at creating partial  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2042640,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "progress or identifying intermediate \nstages that you should focus on first. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2049600,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Going back to this previous discussion, we \ndon't have a way of evaluating partial progress  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2054800,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the same way we can evaluate a one-shot \nsuccess or failure of solving a problem. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2059520,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There's two different ways to think \nthrough what you've just said. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2063040,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "One of them is more bearish on AI \nprogress, and one of them is more bullish. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2066080,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The bearish one being, \"Oh, they're only \ngetting to a certain height of wall,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2069920,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "which is not as high as humans are reaching.\"\nThe second is that they have this powerful  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2076560,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "property that once they achieve a certain \nwaterline, they can fill every single problem  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2081840,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that is available at that waterline, \nwhich we simply can't do with humans. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2085520,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We can't make a million copies of you \nand give each of them a million dollars  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2089840,
    "dDurationMs": 7440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "of inference compute and have you do a hundred \nyears of subjective time research on a million  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2097280,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "different problems at the same time.\nBut once AIs reach Terence Tao-level,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2100640,
    "dDurationMs": 3280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "they could do that.\nOnce they reach intermediate levels,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2103920,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "they could do the intermediate version of that.\nThe same reason that we should be bearish now is  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2109520,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the reason we should be especially bullish.\nNot even when they achieve superhuman  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2112880,
    "dDurationMs": 2160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "intelligence, but just when they \nachieve human-level intelligence,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2115040,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "because their human-level intelligence \nis qualitatively wider and more powerful  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2119680,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "than our human-level intelligence.\nI agree. They excel at breadth,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2124320,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and humans excel at depth, human experts at \nleast. I think they're very complementary.  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2130880,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But our current way of doing math and science \nis focused on depth because that's where human  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2137520,
    "dDurationMs": 8080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "expertise is, because humans can't do breadth.\nWe have to redesign the way we do science to take  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2145600,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "full advantage of this breadth \ncapability that we now have. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2151120,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We should have a lot more effort in creating \nvery broad classes of problems to work on rather  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2155280,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "than one or two really deep, important problems.\nWe should still have the deep, important problems,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2161440,
    "dDurationMs": 7520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and humans should still be working on them.\nBut now we have this other way of doing science. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2170160,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We can explore entirely new fields of \nscience by first getting these broad,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2176000,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "moderately competent AIs to map it out \nand make all the easy observations. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2181520,
    "dDurationMs": 7040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "And then identify certain islands of difficulty, \nwhich human experts can then come and work on. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2189120,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I see very much a future of \nvery complementary science. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2194720,
    "dDurationMs": 7200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Eventually, you would hope to get both breadth \nand depth and somehow get the best of both worlds. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2201920,
    "dDurationMs": 6960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But we need practice with the breadth side. \nIt's too new. We don't even have the paradigms  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2208880,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to really take full advantage of it.\nBut we will, and then science will be  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2214000,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "unrecognizable after that, I think.\nTo this point about complementarity,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2220560,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "programmers have noticed that they're way \nmore productive as a result of these AI tools. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2225680,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I don't know if you as a mathematician \nfeel the same way, but it does seem  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2229520,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "like one big difference between vibe coding \nand vibe researching is that with software,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2236320,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the whole point is to have some \neffect on the world through your work. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2241360,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "If it leads to you better understanding \na problem or coming up with some clean  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2245040,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "abstraction to embody in your code, \nthat is instrumental to the end goal. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2249120,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Whereas with research, the reason we care \nabout solving the Millennium Prize Problems  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2254560,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "is that presumably that in the process of \nsolving them, we discover new mathematical  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2259600,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "objects or new techniques that advance our \ncivilization's understanding of mathematics. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2265840,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So the proof is instrumental \nto the intermediate work. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2270800,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I don't know if you agree with that dichotomy \nor if that in any way will explain the relative  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2277040,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "uplift we'll see in software versus research.\nCertainly in math, the process is often more  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2283200,
    "dDurationMs": 3120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "important than the problem itself.\nThe problem is kind of a proxy  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2286320,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "for measuring progress.\nI think even in software,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2289360,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "there are different types of software tasks.\nIf you just create a webpage that does the same  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2295120,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "thing that a thousand other webpages \ndo, there's no skill to be learned. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2299600,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Well, there is still some skill maybe that \nthe individual programmer could pick up. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2304000,
    "dDurationMs": 8480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But for boilerplate-type code, it's something \nthat you should definitely offload to AI. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2315600,
    "dDurationMs": 2400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Sometimes once you make the code, \nyou still have to maintain it. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2319040,
    "dDurationMs": 2880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There are issues with upgrading it and \nmaking it compatible with other things. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2324720,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I've heard programmers report that even \nif an AI can create the first prototype  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2330800,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "of a tool, making it mesh with everything \nelse and making it interact with the real  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2335280,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "world in the way they want is an ongoing process.\nIf you don't have the skills that you pick up from  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2343520,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "writing the code, that may impact your \nability to maintain it down the road. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2350640,
    "dDurationMs": 8800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So yes, certainly mathematicians, we've used \nproblems to build intuition and to train people  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2359440,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to have a good idea of what's true, what to \nexpect, what is provable, and what is difficult. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2366480,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Just getting the answers right away \nmay actually inhibit that process. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2375280,
    "dDurationMs": 2240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I made a distinction between \ntheory and experiment before. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2379360,
    "dDurationMs": 2880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "In most sciences, there's an equal \ndivision between the theoretical side  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2382240,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and the experimental side.\nMath has been unique in  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2386160,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that it's almost entirely theoretical.\nWe place a premium on trying to have coherent,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2393280,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "clean theories of why things are true and false.\nWe haven't done many experiments as to,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2399120,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "if we have two different ways to solve \na problem, which is more effective. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2404640,
    "dDurationMs": 3280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We have some intuition, but we haven't done \nlarge-scale studies where we take a thousand  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2407920,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "problems and just test them.\nBut we can do that now. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2413120,
    "dDurationMs": 6400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think AI-type tools will actually \nrevolutionize the experimental side of math,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2419520,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "where you don't care so much about individual \nproblems and the process of solving them,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2424880,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but you want to gather large-scale data \nabout what things work and what things don't. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2430000,
    "dDurationMs": 6240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The same way that if you're a software \ncompany and you want to roll out a thousand  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2436240,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "pieces of software, you don't really want to \nhandcraft each one and learn lessons from each. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2439280,
    "dDurationMs": 2720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You just want to find what \nworkflows let you scale. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2446000,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The idea of doing mathematics \nat scale is at its infancy. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2449200,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But that's where AI is really \ngoing to revolutionize the subject. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2453360,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I feel like a big crux in these conversations \nabout how good AI will be for science is,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2458880,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think you said this, that they're using \nexisting techniques and modifying them. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2466000,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It would be interesting to \nunderstand how much progress one  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2469680,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "can make simply from using existing techniques.\nIf I looked at the top math journals, how many of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2475760,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the papers are coming up with a new technique, \nwhatever that means, versus using existing  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2481200,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "techniques on new problems? What is the overhang? \nIf you just applied every known technique to every  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2487200,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "open problem, would that constitute a humongous \nuplift in our civilization's knowledge, or would  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2492560,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that not be that impressive and useful?\nThis is a great question, and we don't  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2498640,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "have the data to fully answer it yet.\nCertainly, a lot of work that human  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2504640,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "mathematicians do… When you take a new problem, \none of the first things we do is we look at all  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2510560,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the standard things that have worked on similar \nproblems in the past, and we try them one by one. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2514640,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Sometimes that works, and that's still worth \npublishing because the question was important. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2519920,
    "dDurationMs": 2000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Sometimes they almost work, \nand you have to add one more  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2521920,
    "dDurationMs": 6960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "wrinkle to it, and that's also interesting.\nBut the papers that go into the top journals  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2528880,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "are usually ones where the existing methods \ncan kind of solve 80% of the problem, but then  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2534560,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "there is this 20% which is resistant and a new \ntechnique has to be invented to fill in the gaps. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2541760,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's very rare now that a problem gets \nsolved with no reliance on past literature,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2546960,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "where all the ideas come out of nowhere.\nThat was more common in the past,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2552880,
    "dDurationMs": 9280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but math is so mature now that it's just so much \nof a handicap to not use the literature first. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2564800,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "AI tools are getting really good at the \nfirst part of that, just trying all the  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2569360,
    "dDurationMs": 6400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "standard techniques on a problem, often making \nfewer mistakes in applying them than humans. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2575760,
    "dDurationMs": 8960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "They still make mistakes, but I've tested \nthese tools on little tasks that I can do,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2584720,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and sometimes they pick up errors that I make.\nSometimes I pick up errors that they make. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2587920,
    "dDurationMs": 8640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's about a tie right now.\nBut I haven't yet seen them take the next step. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2597280,
    "dDurationMs": 6960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "When there are holes in the argument where none \nof the things are working, then what do you do? "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2605360,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "They can suggest random things, but often \nI find that trying to chase them down to  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2611200,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "make them work, and finding they don't \nwork, wastes more time than it saves. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2618560,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think some fraction of problems that \nwe currently think are hard will fall  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2622720,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "from this method, especially the ones \nthat haven't received enough attention. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2628160,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "With the Erdős problems, almost all of the 50 \nproblems that were solved by AIs were ones for  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2633600,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "which there was basically no literature.\nErdős posed the problem once or twice. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2639200,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Maybe some people tried it casually and couldn't \ndo it, but they never wrote up anything. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2643920,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But it turned out that there was a solution, \nand it was just combining this one obscure  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2648640,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "technique that not many people know about \nwith some other result in the literature. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2652720,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "That's the median level of what AI can \naccomplish, and that's really great. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2657440,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It clears out 50 of these problems.\nSo I think you will see some isolated successes. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2664320,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But what we found… Some people have done \nlarge-scale sweeps of these Erdős problems. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2669360,
    "dDurationMs": 2960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "If you only focus on the success \nstories, the ones that get broadcast  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2672320,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "on social media, it looks amazing.\nAll these problems that haven't been  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2675840,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "solved for decades, now they're falling.\nBut whenever we do a systematic study,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2680720,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "on any given problem an AI tool has \na success rate of maybe 1% or 2%. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2686000,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's just that they can buy scale, and you \njust pick the winners. It looks great. I  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2690800,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "think there'll be a similar thing happening \nwith the hundreds of really prestigious,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2697120,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "difficult math problems out there.\nSome AI may get lucky and actually solve them,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2703760,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and there will be some backdoor to solve \nthe problem that everyone else missed. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2708400,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "That will get a lot of publicity.\nBut then people will try these fancy  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2712880,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "tools on their own favorite problem, and they \nwill again experience the 1% to 2% success rate. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2718480,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There'll be a lot of noise amongst the signal \nof when they're working and when they're not. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2728720,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It will be increasingly important to \ncollect these really standardized datasets. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2732640,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There are efforts now to create a standard set of \nchallenge problems for AIs to solve, and not just  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2738160,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "rely on the AI companies to only publish their \nwins and not disclose their negative results. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2744560,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "That will maybe give more clarity \nas to where we're actually at. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2748480,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Although I think it's worth emphasizing how \nmuch progress in AI it constitutes already,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2752080,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to have models that are capable of applying \nsome technique that nobody had written down  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2758080,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "as applicable to this particular problem.\nThe progress is simultaneously amazing  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2762000,
    "dDurationMs": 3280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and disappointing.\nIt is a very strange  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2765280,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "feeling to see these tools in action.\nBut people also acclimatize really quickly. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2772800,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I remember when Google's web \nsearch came out 20 years ago. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2776000,
    "dDurationMs": 2160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It just blew all the other \nsearches out of the water. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2778160,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You're getting relevant hits on the \nfront page, exactly what you wanted. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2783760,
    "dDurationMs": 2480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It was amazing, and then after \na few years, you just took for  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2786240,
    "dDurationMs": 9120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "granted that you could Google anything.\n2026-level AI would be stunning in 2021. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2795360,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "A lot of it—face recognition, natural speech, \ndoing college-level math problems—we just  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2802160,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "take for granted now.\nSpeaking of 2026 AI,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2805520,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "you made a prediction in 2023 that by 2026 \nit would be like a colleague in mathematics? "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2813280,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "A trustworthy co-author if used correctly.\nWhich is looking pretty good in retrospect. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2817280,
    "dDurationMs": 6160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Yeah, I'm pretty pleased.\nSo let's see if you can continue this streak. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2824000,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You personally are 2x more \nproductive as a result of AI. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2828800,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "What year would you say that?\nProductivity, I think,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2832640,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "is not quite a one-dimensional quantity.\nI'm definitely noticing that the style  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2839280,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "in which I do mathematics is changing \nquite a bit, and the type of things I do. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2843440,
    "dDurationMs": 2960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "For example, my papers now have a \nlot more code, a lot more pictures,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2849040,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "because it's so easy to generate these things now.\nSome plot which would have taken me hours to do,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2853760,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "now I can do in minutes.\nBut in the past, I just wouldn't have  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2857120,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "put the plot in my paper in the first place.\nI would just talk about it in words. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2861600,
    "dDurationMs": 9040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So it's hard to measure what 2x means.\nOn the one hand, I think the type of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2870640,
    "dDurationMs": 3440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "papers that I would write today, if I \nhad to do them without AI assistance,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2874080,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "would definitely take five times longer.\nBut I would not write my papers that way. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2878560,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "5x?\nYeah, but these are auxiliary tasks. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2886800,
    "dDurationMs": 6720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Things like doing a much deeper literature \nsearch or supplying a lot more numerics.  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2894480,
    "dDurationMs": 10160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "They enrich the paper. The core of what I do, \nactually solving the most difficult part of a  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2904640,
    "dDurationMs": 3440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "math problem, hasn't changed too much.\nI still use pen and paper for that. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2908080,
    "dDurationMs": 7680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But there's lots of silly things.\nI use an AI agent now to reformat. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2915760,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Sometimes if all my parentheses are not quite \nthe right size, I used to manually change them  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2919680,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "by hand, and now I can get an AI agent to \ndo all that quite nicely in the background. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2926800,
    "dDurationMs": 7040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "They've really sped up lots of secondary tasks.\nThey haven't yet sped up the core thing that I do,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2933840,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but it's allowed me to add \nmore things to my papers. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2940800,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "By the same token, if I were to write a paper \nI wrote in 2020 again—and not add all these  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2946000,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "extra features, but just have something of \nthe same level of functionality—it actually  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2951600,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "hasn't saved that much time, to be honest.\nIt's made the papers richer and broader,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2957360,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but not necessarily deeper.\nYou made this distinction between  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2962160,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "artificial cleverness and artificial intelligence.\nI would like to better understand those concepts. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2969280,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "What is an example of intelligence \nthat is not just cleverness? "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2980080,
    "dDurationMs": 1840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Intelligence is famously hard to define. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2981920,
    "dDurationMs": 2080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's one of these things that \nyou know when you see it. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2985280,
    "dDurationMs": 7200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But when I talk to someone and we're trying to \ncollaboratively solve a math problem together,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 2993440,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "there's this conversation where neither of \nus knows how to solve the problem initially. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3000080,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "One of us has some idea and it looks promising, \nso then we have some sort of prototype strategy. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3006400,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We test it, and it doesn't \nwork, but then we modify it. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3010480,
    "dDurationMs": 7760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There's adaptivity and continual \nimprovement of the idea over time. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3018240,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Eventually, we've systematically mapped \nout what doesn't work and what does work,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3023760,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and we can see a path forward, but \nit's evolving with our discussion. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3030720,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This isn't quite what the AIs do.\nThe AIs can mimic this a little bit. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3037280,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "To go back to this analogy of these jumping \nrobots, they can jump and fail, and jump and fail. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3044320,
    "dDurationMs": 8400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But what they can't do is jump a little bit, reach \nsome handhold, stay there, pull other people up,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3052720,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and then try to jump from there.\nThere isn't this cumulative process  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3058560,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "which is built up interactively.\nIt seems to be a lot more trial and  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3064640,
    "dDurationMs": 7520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "error and just repetition: brute force.\nIt scales, and it can work amazingly  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3072160,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "well in certain contexts.\nBut this idea of building  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3077520,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "up cumulatively from partial progress \nis what's still not quite there yet. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3083280,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Interesting. You're saying if Gemini 3 or \nClaude 4.5, whatever, solves a problem,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3089760,
    "dDurationMs": 2760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it is not the case that its own \nunderstanding of math has progressed. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3092520,
    "dDurationMs": 920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "No.\nOr even if it works  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3093440,
    "dDurationMs": 3440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "on a problem without solving it, it's not that \nits own understanding of math has progressed. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3096880,
    "dDurationMs": 3280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Yeah. You run a new session and \nit's forgotten what it just did. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3100160,
    "dDurationMs": 9680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It has no new skills to build on related problems.\nMaybe what you just did is 0.001% of the  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3109840,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "training data for the next generation.\nSo maybe eventually some of it gets absorbed. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3114640,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So Terence talks about the importance \nof decomposing particularly gnarly  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3118000,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "problems into a series of easier chunks.\nEven if this doesn't result in the full solution,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3123360,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "approaching problems in this way helps you build \nup the intuitions and practice the techniques  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3127840,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that you'll need to keep making progress.\nBut models today tend to struggle with these  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3131680,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "kinds of problem-solving techniques.\nThat's where Labelbox comes in. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3134720,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Labelbox helps you train models not just to get \nthe right answer, but to think the right way. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3139280,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "They've operationalized these reasoning behaviors \ninto rubrics, giving you the ability to evaluate  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3144160,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "every important dimension of a model's output.\nThese rubrics go beyond simple correctness. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3148800,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Did the model reach for the right tools?\nDid it check its own work and  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3151840,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "explore alternative paths?\nHow clear was its response? "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3155520,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "These skills are useful across domains: \nmath, physics, finance, psychology, and more. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3160560,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "And they're becoming increasingly important \nas models take on harder, open-ended problems,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3164960,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "some of which have multiple solutions and some \nof which we don't even know the solutions to. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3168800,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Labelbox can get you rubrics tailored to \nyour domain, helping you systematically  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3172320,
    "dDurationMs": 8320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "measure and shape how your models think.\nLearn more at labelbox.com/dwarkesh. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3180640,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "One big question I have is how plausible is it \nthat if we just keep training AIs—they get better  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3186480,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and better at solving problems in Lean—that they \nwill continue to solve more and more impressive  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3192000,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "problems, and then we will be surprised at how \nlittle insight we got from some Lean solution  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3198000,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to proving the Riemann hypothesis or something.\nOr do you think it is a necessary condition of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3202000,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "solving the Riemann hypothesis, even by \nan AI that is doing it entirely in Lean,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3205360,
    "dDurationMs": 7520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that the constructions and definitions \ncreated in the Lean program have to  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3212880,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "advance our understanding of mathematics?\nOr could it just be assembly code gobbledygook? "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3220000,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We don't know. Some problems have been \nbasically solved by pure brute force. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3224320,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The four color theorem is a famous example.\nWe have still not found a conceptually elegant  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3229360,
    "dDurationMs": 7040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "proof of this theorem, and maybe we never will.\nSome problems may only be solvable by splitting  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3236400,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "into an enormous number of \ncases and doing brute force,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3240560,
    "dDurationMs": 8000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "uninsightful computer analysis on each case.\nPart of the reason we prize problems like  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3248560,
    "dDurationMs": 6400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the Riemann hypothesis is that we're \npretty sure a new type of mathematics  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3254960,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "has to be created, or a new connection between \ntwo previously unconnected areas of mathematics  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3258960,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "has to be discovered to make this work.\nWe don't even know what the shape of the solution  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3264560,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "is, but it doesn't feel like a problem that will \nbe solved just by exhaustively checking cases. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3270400,
    "dDurationMs": 6880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Or it could be false actually.\nOkay, there is an unlikely scenario  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3277280,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that the hypothesis is false, and you \ncan just compute a zero off the line,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3282320,
    "dDurationMs": 8720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and a massive computer calculation verifies \nit. That would be very disappointing. I do  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3291040,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "feel that fully autonomous, one-shot approaches \nare not the right approach for these problems. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3299200,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You'll get a lot more mileage out of the interplay \nof humans collaborating with these tools. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3308080,
    "dDurationMs": 6480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I can see one of these problems \nbeing solved by smart humans  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3314560,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "assisted by extremely powerful AI tools.\nBut the exact dynamic may be very different  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3320560,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "from what we envision right now.\nIt could be a collaboration of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3324480,
    "dDurationMs": 10720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "a type that just doesn't exist yet.\nThere may be a way to generate a million variants  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3335200,
    "dDurationMs": 6720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "of the Riemann zeta function and do AI-assisted \ndata analysis to discover some pattern connecting  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3341920,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "them that we didn't know about before.\nThis lets you transform the problem  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3346400,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "into a different area of mathematics.\nThere could be all kinds of scenarios. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3351200,
    "dDurationMs": 8640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Suppose the AI figures it out, and latent in \nthe Lean is some brand-new construction which,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3359840,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "if we realized its significance, we would be \nable to apply in all these different situations. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3364720,
    "dDurationMs": 6880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "How would we even recognize it?\nAgain, a very naive question, but if you come  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3371600,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "up with the equivalent of Descartes' idea that \nyou can have a coordinate system unifying algebra  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3377040,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and geometry, in Lean code it would just look \nlike R→R, and it wouldn't look that significant. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3382560,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I'm sure there are other constructions \nwhich have this kind of property. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3386160,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The beauty of formalizing a proof in \nsomething like Lean is that you can take  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3389520,
    "dDurationMs": 9520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "any piece of it and study it atomically.\nWhen I read a paper which solves some  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3399040,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "difficult problem, there's often a \nbig sequence of lemmas and theorems. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3404880,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Ideally, the author will talk their way \nthrough what's important and what's not. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3408480,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But sometimes they don't reveal what steps \nwere the important ones and which ones  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3412880,
    "dDurationMs": 6480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "were just boilerplate, standard steps.\nYou can study each lemma in isolation. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3419360,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Some of them I can see look fairly standard \nand resemble something I'm familiar with. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3424000,
    "dDurationMs": 2320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I'm pretty sure there's nothing \ninteresting going on there. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3426320,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But this other lemma, that's something I haven't \nseen before, and I can see why having this result  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3432080,
    "dDurationMs": 7440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "would really help prove the main result.\nYou can assess whether a step is really key  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3441280,
    "dDurationMs": 2960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to your argument or not, and \nLean really facilitates that. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3446240,
    "dDurationMs": 2480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The individual steps are \nidentified really precisely. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3449520,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think in the future, there will be entire \nprofessions of mathematicians who might take  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3455040,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "a giant Lean-generated proof and do some \nablation on it, trying to remove parts of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3461120,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it and find more elegant ways.\nThey might get other AIs to do  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3466400,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "some reinforcement learning to make the proof \nmore elegant, and maybe other AIs will grade  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3472160,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "whether this proof looks better or not.\nOne thing that will change quite a bit  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3478000,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "in the near future is how we write papers.\nUntil recently, writing papers was the most  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3481920,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "time-consuming and expensive part of the job.\nSo you did it very rarely. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3487760,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You only wrote up your results once all the other \nparts of your argument were checked out, because  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3494560,
    "dDurationMs": 4800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "rewriting and refactoring was just a total pain.\nThat's become a lot easier now  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3499360,
    "dDurationMs": 2240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "with modern AI tools.\nYou don't have to have just  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3501600,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "one version of your paper.\nOnce you have one,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3504960,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "people can generate hundreds more.\nOne giant messy Lean proof may not be very  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3511040,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "meaningful or understandable on \nits own, but other people can  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3515360,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "refactor it and do all kinds of things with it.\nWe've seen this with the Erdős problem website. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3522960,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "An AI will generate a proof, and here are \n3,000 lines of code that verify the proof. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3527840,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Then people got other AIs to summarize \nthe proof, and people write their own  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3532560,
    "dDurationMs": 7920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "proofs. There's actually post-processing. \nOnce you have one proof, we have a lot of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3540480,
    "dDurationMs": 7280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "tools now to deconstruct and interpret it.\nIt's a very nascent area of mathematics,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3547760,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but I'm not as worried about it.\nSome people are concerned about what happens if  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3552000,
    "dDurationMs": 2880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the Riemann hypothesis is proven with \na completely incomprehensible proof. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3554880,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think once you have the artifact of a \nproof, we can do a lot of analysis on it. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3560640,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You posted recently that it would be \nhelpful to have a formal or semi-formal  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3564960,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "language for mathematical strategies \nas opposed to just mathematical proofs,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3568960,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "which is what Lean specializes in.\nI would love to learn more about  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3572160,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "what that would involve or look like.\nWe don't really know. We've been very  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3577840,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "lucky in mathematics that we have worked \nout the laws of logic and mathematics,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3582400,
    "dDurationMs": 5520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but this is a fairly recent accomplishment.\nIt was started by Euclid two millennia ago,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3587920,
    "dDurationMs": 6720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but only in the early 20th century did we \nfinally list out the axioms of mathematics,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3594640,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the standard axioms of what we call ZFC, the \naxioms of first-order logic, and what a proof is. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3600400,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This we've managed to automate \nand have a formal language for. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3605840,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There could be some way to assess plausibility.\nYou have a conjecture that something is true,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3614080,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "you test a few examples, and it works out.\nHow does this increase your  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3618240,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "confidence that the conjecture is true?\nWe have a few sort of mathematical ways to model  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3624560,
    "dDurationMs": 7760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "this, like Bayesian probability, for example.\nBut you often have to set certain base  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3632320,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "assumptions, and there's a lot of \nsubjectivity still in these tasks. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3644880,
    "dDurationMs": 7360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This is more of a wish than a plan to develop \nthese languages, but just seeing how successful  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3652240,
    "dDurationMs": 7600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "having a formal framework in place, like Lean, has \nmade deductive proofs so much easier to automate  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3659840,
    "dDurationMs": 10480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and train AI on… The bottleneck for using AI to \ncreate strategies and make conjectures is we have  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3670320,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to rely on human experts and the test of time to \nvalidate whether something is plausible or not. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3676880,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "If there was some semi-formal framework \nwhere this could be done semi-automatically  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3682480,
    "dDurationMs": 9760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "in a way that isn't easily hackable...\nIt's really important with these formal  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3692240,
    "dDurationMs": 8480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "proof assistants that there are no backdoors \nor exploits you can use to somehow get your  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3700720,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "certified proof without actually proving \nit, because reinforcement learning is  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3704960,
    "dDurationMs": 11200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "just so good at finding these backdoors.\nIf there's some framework that mimics how  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3716160,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "scientists talk to each other in a \nsemi-formal way, using data and argument,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3721280,
    "dDurationMs": 7680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but also constructing narratives...\nThere's some subjective aspect of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3728960,
    "dDurationMs": 6720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "science that we don't know how to capture in a way \nthat we can insert AI into it in any useful way.  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3738160,
    "dDurationMs": 7440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This is a future problem. There are research \nefforts to try to create automated conjectures,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3747360,
    "dDurationMs": 8080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and maybe there are ways to benchmark these and \nsimulate this, but it's all very new science. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3755440,
    "dDurationMs": 9840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Can you help me get some intuition? I have two \nsub-questions. One, it would be very helpful  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3765280,
    "dDurationMs": 10960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to have a specific example of what something \nlike this would look like, the way scientists  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3776240,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "communicate that we can't formalize yet.\nTwo, it seems almost definitionally paradoxical  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3782000,
    "dDurationMs": 8160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to say you're building up some narrative or \nnatural language explanation and then also having  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3790160,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "something which you could have formalized.\nI'm sure there's some intuition behind  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3796160,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "where that overlap is, and I'd \nlove to understand that better. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3800400,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "An example of a conjecture: Gauss was \ninterested in the prime numbers and  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3808000,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "created one of the first mathematical datasets.\nHe just computed the first 100,000 prime numbers  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3811760,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "or so, hoping to find patterns.\nHe did find a pattern,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3817120,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but maybe not the pattern he was expecting.\nHe found a statistical pattern in the primes  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3821120,
    "dDurationMs": 6400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that if you count how many primes there are \nup to 100, 1,000, one million, and so forth,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3827520,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "they get sparser and sparser, but the drop-off \nin the density was inversely proportional to  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3834080,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the natural logarithm of the range of numbers.\nSo he conjectured what we now call the prime  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3839360,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "number theorem: the number of primes up \nto X is X divided by the natural log of X. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3845120,
    "dDurationMs": 6960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "He had no way to prove this. It was \ndata-driven. This was a conjecture.  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3852880,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It was revolutionary for its time because it \nwas maybe the first really important conjecture  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3859520,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "of math that was statistical in nature.\nNormally you're talking about a pattern,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3863840,
    "dDurationMs": 2480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "like maybe the spacing between the \nprimes has a certain regularity. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3867600,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But this didn't tell you exactly how many \nprimes there were in any given range. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3872000,
    "dDurationMs": 6880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It just gave you an approximation that got better \nand better as you went further and further out. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3882640,
    "dDurationMs": 2560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It started the field of what \nwe call analytic number theory. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3887040,
    "dDurationMs": 4000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It was the first in many conjectures \nlike this, many of which got proved,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3891040,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "which started consolidating the idea that the \nprime numbers didn't really have a pattern,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3896880,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that they behaved like random sets \nof numbers with a certain density. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3903360,
    "dDurationMs": 2320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "They had some patterns, \nlike they're almost all odd. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3907760,
    "dDurationMs": 1920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "They're also not actually random, \nthey're what's called pseudo-random. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3910800,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There's no random number generation \ninvolved in creating the prime numbers. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3914160,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But over time, it became more and more \nproductive to think of the primes as  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3919600,
    "dDurationMs": 6400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "if they were just generated by some god rolling \ndice all the time and creating this random set. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3926000,
    "dDurationMs": 1840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "This allowed us to make all \nthese other predictions. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3928480,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There's a still-open conjecture in number \ntheory called the twin prime conjecture, that  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3932640,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "there should be infinitely many pairs of primes \nthat are twins just two apart, like 11 and 13. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3937200,
    "dDurationMs": 2640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We can't prove that, and there are \ngood reasons why we can't prove it. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3941040,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But because of this statistical random model of \nthe primes, we are absolutely convinced it's true. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3946240,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We know that if the primes were generated by \nflipping coins, we would just—by random chance  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3951680,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "like infinite monkeys at a typewriter—see \ntwin primes appear over and over again. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3957440,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We have over time developed this very accurate \nconceptual model of what the primes should behave  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3962320,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "like based on statistics and probability.\nIt's mostly heuristic and non-rigorous,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3967920,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but extremely accurate.\nThe few times when we actually  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3972400,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "can prove things about the primes, it has \nmatched up with the predictions of what we  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3976480,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "call the random model of the primes.\nWe have this conjectural concept  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3981600,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "framework for understanding the \nprimes that everyone believes in. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3985920,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's the same reason why we believe the \nRiemann hypothesis is true, and why we  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3989680,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "believe that cryptography based on \nthe primes is mathematically secure. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 3995120,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's all part of this belief.\nIn fact, one reason why we care  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4000800,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "about the Riemann hypothesis is that \nif the Riemann hypothesis failed,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4004320,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "if we knew it was false, it would \nbe a serious blow to this model. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4009920,
    "dDurationMs": 3440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It would mean there's a secret pattern \nto the primes that we were not aware of. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4014720,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think we would very rapidly abandon \nany cryptography based on the primes,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4018080,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "because if there was one pattern that we didn't \nknow about, there are probably more, and these  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4021760,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "patterns can lead to exploits in crypto.\nIt would be a big shock. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4027680,
    "dDurationMs": 2960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So we really want to make \nsure that doesn't happen. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4035360,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We've been convinced of things like \nthe Riemann hypothesis over time. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4040320,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Some of it is experimental evidence, and some \nis that the few times we've been able to make  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4044080,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "theoretical results, they've always aligned.\nIt is possible that the consensus is wrong and  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4050000,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "we've all just missed something very basic.\nThere have been paradigm shifts in  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4054720,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the past in scientific history.\nBut we don't really have a way of  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4060480,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "measuring this, partly because we don't have \nenough data on how math or science develops. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4066800,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We have one timeline of history, and we have \nmaybe 100 stories of turning points in history. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4073600,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "If we had access to a million alien \ncivilizations, each with a different  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4078640,
    "dDurationMs": 6080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "development of history and science in different \norders, then maybe we'd actually have a decent  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4084720,
    "dDurationMs": 7840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "shot at understanding how we measure what \nprogress is and what is a good strategy. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4092560,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We could maybe start formalizing \nit and actually having a framework. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4098320,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Maybe what we need to do is start creating \nlots of mini-universes or simulations of AI  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4104880,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "solving very basic problems in arithmetic \nor whatever, but coming up with their  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4110240,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "own strategies for doing these things and \nhaving these little laboratories to test. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4114480,
    "dDurationMs": 5040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There are people who investigate what's \nthe smallest neural network that can do  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4119520,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "10-digit multiplication and things like that.\nI think we could learn a lot just from evolving  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4125680,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "small AIs on simple problems.\nI was super excited when Mercury  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4130880,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "reached out about sponsoring the podcast \nbecause I've been banking with them for years. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4134480,
    "dDurationMs": 2240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think I opened my first \naccount with them in 2023. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4136720,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Something I've come to appreciate over the \nlast few years is that Mercury is constantly  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4139760,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "updating things and adding new features.\nTake their newest feature, Insights. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4143440,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Insights summarizes your money in and out, \nshowing you your biggest transactions and calling  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4147360,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "out anything that deserves extra attention.\nLike maybe your revenue from a particular partner  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4151680,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "has gone down, or you've got a big uncategorized \npurchase that needs to be investigated. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4155440,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's a super low-friction way for me to keep \ntabs on my business and make quick decisions. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4159200,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "For example, I try to invest any cash that I \ndon't need on hand to keep running the business. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4163440,
    "dDurationMs": 3440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "With Insights, with just a couple of clicks, \nI was able to see exactly how much money I  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4166880,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "spent in each month of 2025 and that lets \nme know exactly how much cash I'll need for  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4171840,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the next year or so of operations.\nAnd then I can go invest the rest. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4175040,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Mercury just keeps adding new features like this.\nGo to mercury.com to check it out. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4179760,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Mercury is a fintech company, \nnot an FDIC Insured Bank. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4182960,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Banking services provided through Choice \nFinancial Group and Column NA, members FDIC. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4188880,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You have to learn about new fields not \nonly very rapidly, but deeply enough  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4193440,
    "dDurationMs": 3760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to contribute to the frontier.\nSo in some sense, you're also  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4197200,
    "dDurationMs": 7600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "one of the world's greatest autodidacts.\nWhat is your process of learning about a new  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4204800,
    "dDurationMs": 7680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "subfield in math? What does that look like?\nWe talked about depth and breadth before. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4212480,
    "dDurationMs": 6880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's not a purely human-AI distinction.\nHumans also, I think it was Berlin who  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4219360,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "split them into hedgehogs and foxes.\nThe hedgehog knows one thing very well,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4223280,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and a fox knows a little bit about everything.\nI definitely think of myself as a fox. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4232240,
    "dDurationMs": 3120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I work with hedgehogs a lot, and \nsometimes I can be a hedgehog if need be. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4240240,
    "dDurationMs": 3040,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I've always had a little \nbit of an obsessive streak. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4243280,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "If there's something I read about which I \nfeel like I have the capability to understand,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4248480,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but I don't understand why it works and \nthere's some magic in it… Someone was able  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4253680,
    "dDurationMs": 4640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to use a type of mathematics I'm not familiar \nwith and get a result I would like to prove. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4258320,
    "dDurationMs": 3120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I can't do it myself, but they \ncould do it by their method,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4261440,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "and I want to find out what their trick was.\nIt bugs me that someone else can do something  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4266800,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think I can do, but I can't.\nI've always had that obsessive,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4270960,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "completionist streak.\nI've had to wean myself off  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4274160,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "computer games because if I start a game, I want \nto play it to completion, through all the levels. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4283840,
    "dDurationMs": 6000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "That's one way I learn new fields.\nI collaborate with a lot of people  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4289840,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "who have taught me other types of mathematics.\nI just make friends with another mathematician  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4295520,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "working on another area of mathematics.\nI find their problems interesting,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4298880,
    "dDurationMs": 5600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but they have to teach me some of the basic \ntricks, what's known, and what's not known. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4304480,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I learn a lot from that.\nI found that writing about  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4309840,
    "dDurationMs": 2560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "what I've learned helps.\nI have a blog where I sometimes  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4314800,
    "dDurationMs": 3520,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "record things I've learned.\nIn the past when I was younger,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4318320,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I would learn something, do this cool trick, \nand say, \"Okay, I'm going to remember this.\" "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4322240,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Then six months later, I'd forgotten it.\nI remember remembering it,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4327440,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but I can't reconstruct my arguments.\nThe first few times, it was so frustrating  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4331040,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to have understood something and then lost it.\nI resolved I should always write down  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4336960,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "anything cool that I've learned.\nThat's part of how this blog came about. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4342720,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "How long does it take you to write a blog post?\nIt's something I often do when I don't want  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4347840,
    "dDurationMs": 2320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to do other work.\nThere's some referee  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4350160,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "report or something that feels slightly \nunpleasant for me to do at the time. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4355760,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Writing a blog feels creative and fun.\nIt's something I do for myself. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4362400,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Depending on the topic, it could be a \nquick half an hour or several hours. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4369360,
    "dDurationMs": 8640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Because it's something I do voluntarily, \ntime flies when I write these things down, as  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4378000,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "opposed to doing something I have to do for \nadministrative reasons that is just drudgery. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4383680,
    "dDurationMs": 2400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Those are tasks, by the way, that \nAI is really helping with nowadays. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4387760,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "If civilization could from first principles \ndecide how to use Terry Tao's time, as a  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4394560,
    "dDurationMs": 7920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "limited resource, what is the biggest difference?\nWhat if the veil of ignorance got to decide how to  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4402480,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "use Terry Tao's time versus what it does \nnow? This podcast wouldn't be happening. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4409760,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "As much as I complain about certain tasks that \nI don't want to do, but have to do… As you get  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4414720,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "more senior in academia, you get more and more \nresponsibilities, more committees, and whatever. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4422000,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I have also found that a lot of events \nI reluctantly went to because I was  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4427680,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "obliged to for one reason or another… \nBecause it's outside my comfort zone,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4431600,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "it often results in interactions with people I \nwouldn't normally talk to, like you for instance. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4437520,
    "dDurationMs": 2480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I would learn interesting things \nand have interesting experiences. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4441760,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I would have opportunities to then network with \nother people that I never would have before. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4448160,
    "dDurationMs": 9840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "So I do believe a lot in serendipity.\nI do optimize portions of my day  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4458000,
    "dDurationMs": 6720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "where I schedule very carefully.\nBut I am willing to leave some portions just  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4465280,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to do something that is not my usual thing.\nMaybe it'll be a waste of my time,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4469600,
    "dDurationMs": 8560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but maybe I will learn something.\nMore often than not, I get a positive  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4478160,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "experience that I wouldn't have planned for.\nSo I believe a lot in serendipity. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4485360,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Maybe there's a danger in modern \nsocieties, not just with AI, that we've  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4490080,
    "dDurationMs": 7360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "become really good at optimizing everything.\nWe’re not optimizing our own optimization. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4499440,
    "dDurationMs": 7200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "With COVID, for example, we switched a lot to \nremote meetings, so everything was scheduled.  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4507920,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "We kept busy in academia. We met almost \nthe same number of people we met in person,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4514480,
    "dDurationMs": 8160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but everything had to be planned in advance.\nWhat we lost out on was the casual knocking  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4522640,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "on a hallway door, just meeting \nsomeone while getting a coffee. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4528000,
    "dDurationMs": 9200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Those serendipitous interactions may not seem \noptimal, but they are actually really important. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4537200,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "When I was a grad student, I would go to \nthe library to look for a journal article. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4542640,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You had to physically check out \nthe journal and read the article. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4546960,
    "dDurationMs": 4480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You could browse through and sometimes \nthe next article was also interesting. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4552160,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Sometimes it wasn’t, but you could \naccidentally find interesting things. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4556960,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "That has basically been lost now.\nIf you want to access an article,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4562080,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "you just type it into a search engine or an AI, \nand you get exactly what you want instantly. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4566480,
    "dDurationMs": 7360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But you don't get the accidental things you might \nhave found if you'd done it more inefficiently. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4580320,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I spent a year once at the Institute \nfor Advanced Study, which is  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4583920,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "a great place with no distractions.\nYou're there just to do research. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4589440,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The first few weeks you're there, it's great.\nYou're getting all these papers written up that  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4593120,
    "dDurationMs": 2320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "you've been wanting to do for a long time.\nYou think about problems for  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4595440,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "blocks of hours at a time.\nBut I find if I stay there for more  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4599040,
    "dDurationMs": 7840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "than several months, I run out of inspiration. \nI get bored. I surf the internet a lot more. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4606880,
    "dDurationMs": 3200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You actually do need a certain \nlevel of distraction in your life. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4610080,
    "dDurationMs": 12480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It adds enough randomness and high temperature.\nI don't know the optimal way to schedule  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4622560,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "my life. It just seems to work.\nI'm very curious when you expect AIs  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4628000,
    "dDurationMs": 7360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that can actually do frontier math at least \nas well as the best human mathematicians. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4635920,
    "dDurationMs": 5440,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "In some ways, they're already doing frontier math \nthat is super intelligent that humans can't do,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4641360,
    "dDurationMs": 2240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but it's a different frontier \nfrom what we're used to. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4644320,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You could argue that calculators were doing \nfrontier math that humans could not accomplish,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4649440,
    "dDurationMs": 9360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "but it was number crunching.\nBut replacing Terry Tao completely. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4658800,
    "dDurationMs": 9200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I mean, what do you want me for?\nYou'll just go on all the podcasts after. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4670800,
    "dDurationMs": 10240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It might not be the right question to ask.\nI think within a decade, a lot of things that  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4681040,
    "dDurationMs": 5280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "math students currently do—what we spend the \nbulk of our time doing and a lot of stuff we  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4686320,
    "dDurationMs": 6400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "put in our papers today—can be done by AI.\nBut we will find that that actually wasn't  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4692720,
    "dDurationMs": 7680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the most important part of what we do.\nA hundred years ago, a lot of mathematicians  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4700400,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "were just solving differential equations.\nPhysicists needed some exact solution to  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4707440,
    "dDurationMs": 5760,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "some system, and they hired a mathematician to \nlaboriously go through the calculus and work out  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4713200,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "the solution to this fluid equation, whatever.\nA lot of what a 19th-century mathematician would  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4720000,
    "dDurationMs": 6320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "do, you could make a call to Mathematica, Wolfram \nAlpha, a computer algebra package, or now more  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4726320,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "recently to an AI, and it would just solve the \nproblem in a few minutes. But we moved on. We  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4733120,
    "dDurationMs": 4720,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "worked on different types of problems after that.\nOnce computers came along—computers  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4739120,
    "dDurationMs": 1920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "used to be human.\nPeople used to laboriously  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4741040,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "create log tables and work out primes as \nGauss did, and that has all been outsourced  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4745920,
    "dDurationMs": 10160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "to computers. But we moved on. In genetics, \nto sequence the genome of a single organism,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4756080,
    "dDurationMs": 7360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that was an entire PhD of a geneticist, carefully \nseparating all the chromosomes and whatever. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4763440,
    "dDurationMs": 3360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Now you can just spend $1,000 and send \nit to a sequencer and get it done. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4766800,
    "dDurationMs": 4240,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But genetics is not dead as a subject.\nYou move to a different scale. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4771040,
    "dDurationMs": 3120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Maybe you study whole ecosystems \nrather than individuals. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4774160,
    "dDurationMs": 4160,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I take your point but when is most \nmathematical progress, or almost  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4778320,
    "dDurationMs": 4880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "all mathematical progress, happening by AI?\nIf you find out this year a Millennium Prize  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4783200,
    "dDurationMs": 6640,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Problem has been solved, you would put \n95% odds that an AI did it autonomously. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4789840,
    "dDurationMs": 6880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Surely there will be such a year.\nI guess I do believe that hybrid  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4797600,
    "dDurationMs": 7120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "human plus AIs will dominate mathematics for \na lot longer. It will depend. It will require  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4804720,
    "dDurationMs": 5120,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "some additional breakthroughs beyond what we \nalready have, so it's going to be stochastic. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4811120,
    "dDurationMs": 4080,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "I think AIs currently are very good at \ncertain things, but really terrible at others. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4816560,
    "dDurationMs": 6800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "While you can add more and more frameworks on top \nto reduce the error rates and make them work with  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4823360,
    "dDurationMs": 10000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "each other a bit more, it feels like we don't \nhave all the ingredients to really have a truly  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4833360,
    "dDurationMs": 6960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "satisfactory replacement for all intellectual \ntasks. It is complementary currently. It's not  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4842720,
    "dDurationMs": 11600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "a replacement. Because current level AIs \nwill accelerate science in so many ways,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4854320,
    "dDurationMs": 5680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "hopefully new discoveries and new \nbreakthroughs will happen more quickly. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4861200,
    "dDurationMs": 5200,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's also possible that by destroying serendipity \nwe actually inhibit certain types of progress. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4867200,
    "dDurationMs": 3840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Anything is possible at this point.\nI think the world is very,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4871040,
    "dDurationMs": 5360,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "very unpredictable at this point in time.\nWhat is your advice to somebody who would  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4876400,
    "dDurationMs": 9280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "consider a career in math or is early in a career \nin math, especially in light of AI progress? "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4885680,
    "dDurationMs": 2000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "How should they be thinking about \ntheir career differently, if at all,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4887680,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "as a result of AI progress?\nWe live in a time of change. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4892480,
    "dDurationMs": 3600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "As I said, we live in a \nparticularly unpredictable era. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4901280,
    "dDurationMs": 4400,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "Things that we've taken for granted \nfor centuries may not hold anymore. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4908240,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "The way we do everything, and not \njust mathematics, will change. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4919600,
    "dDurationMs": 3680,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "In many ways, I would prefer the much more \nboring, quiet era where things are much the  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4923280,
    "dDurationMs": 8000,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "same as they were 10 years ago, 20 years ago.\nBut I think one just has to embrace that  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4932000,
    "dDurationMs": 6560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "there's going to be a lot of change.\nThe things that you study, some of them  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4938560,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "may become obsolete or revolutionized, \nbut some things will be retained. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4946720,
    "dDurationMs": 8480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You always have to keep an eye on opportunities \nfor things that you wouldn't be able to do before. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4957680,
    "dDurationMs": 4560,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "In math, you previously had to go through \nyears and years of education and be a math  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4962240,
    "dDurationMs": 2800,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "PhD before you could contribute \nto the frontier of math research. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4966160,
    "dDurationMs": 2880,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But now it's quite possible at the \nhigh school level, or whatever,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4969040,
    "dDurationMs": 3280,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "that you could get involved in a math project and \nactually make a real contribution because of all  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4972320,
    "dDurationMs": 5840,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "these AI tools, Lean, and everything else.\nThere will be a lot of non-traditional  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4978160,
    "dDurationMs": 5920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "opportunities to learn, so you \nneed a very adaptable mindset. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4986640,
    "dDurationMs": 3920,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "There will be room for pursuing things \njust for curiosity and for playing around. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4991840,
    "dDurationMs": 4320,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "You still need to get your credentials.\nFor a while it will still be important to  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 4997440,
    "dDurationMs": 6480,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "go through traditional education and learn \nmath and science the old-fashioned way. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 5008080,
    "dDurationMs": 7600,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "But you should also be open to very different ways \nof doing science, some of which don't exist yet. "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 5017360,
    "dDurationMs": 4960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "It's a scary time, but also very exciting.\nThat's a great note to close on. Terence,  "
    } ]
  }, {
    "tStartMs": 5022320,
    "dDurationMs": 960,
    "segs": [ {
      "utf8": "thanks so much.\nPleasure."
    } ]
  } ]
}
